    <h2>1.1 Why Focus on Fundamentals Instead of Just Technical Analysis</h2>
    
    <h3>üìå Technical Analysis</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Definition</strong>: Predicting future trends through charts of stock prices and trading volume.</li>
        <li><strong>Advantages</strong>: Intuitive, can see market sentiment, commonly used by short-term traders.</li>
        <li><strong>Disadvantages</strong>:
            <ol>
                <li>Over-reliance on charts may ignore the real situation of the company.</li>
                <li>Short-term price movements are difficult to predict, easy to "chase rising and falling prices".</li>
                <li><strong>Miss long-term opportunities</strong>: If you only look at charts, in 2000 you might think Amazon crashed, ignoring its later growth into a world giant.</li>
            </ol>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>üìå Fundamental Analysis</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Definition</strong>: Study the company's operating conditions, financial health, and industry prospects to determine "whether the company is worth investing in".</li>
        <li><strong>Advantages</strong>:
            <ol>
                <li>Sustainable in the long term, avoiding short-term speculation.</li>
                <li>Make investment "buying a business" instead of "buying a lottery ticket".</li>
                <li>Help discover undervalued good companies.</li>
            </ol>
        </li>
    </ul>
    
    <blockquote>
        ‚ö†Ô∏è Case:
        <ul>
            <li>2000 Internet bubble: Many companies' stock prices soared, but had no profits, resulting in a crash.</li>
            <li>Although Amazon lost money for many years, financial reports showed sustained high revenue growth, and fundamentals supported its long-term success.</li>
        </ul>
    </blockquote>
    
    <p>üëâ <strong>Summary</strong>: Technical analysis is a "sentiment thermometer", fundamental analysis is the "health check report". Investment should focus on fundamentals, with technical analysis as a supplement.</p>
    
    <h2>1.2 How to Research a Company's Fundamentals</h2>
    
    <h3>üîç Step 1: Search for Company Financial Reports on Google</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Search keywords: <code>Apple investor relations</code> or <code>Google annual report</code>.</li>
        <li>Official Investor Relations page ‚Üí Find <strong>Annual Report (10-K)</strong>, <strong>Quarterly Report (10-Q)</strong>.</li>
        <li><strong>Advantages</strong>: Most authoritative, directly from the company.</li>
        <li><strong>Disadvantages</strong>: Content is too long (hundreds of pages), difficult for beginners to quickly extract.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>üîç Step 2: Use Google Finance</h3>
    <ol>
        <li>Open Google</li>
        <li>Enter stock ticker:
            <ul>
                <li>Apple ‚Üí <code>AAPL</code></li>
                <li>Google ‚Üí <code>GOOG</code></li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>You can see:
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Summary</strong> ‚Üí Market cap, P/E ratio, dividend yield</li>
                <li><strong>Financials</strong> ‚Üí Income statement, balance sheet, cash flow</li>
                <li><strong>Statistics</strong> ‚Üí Valuation metrics (P/E, PEG, etc.)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ol>
    
    <h3>üîç Step 3: Cross-verify with Financial News</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Relevant news on Google News or Bloomberg, combined with financial data, to avoid "only looking at numbers without the story".</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>1.3 Case Study: Google and Apple</h2>
    
    <h3>üçè Apple (AAPL)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>2023 Financial data (simplified):
            <ul>
                <li>Revenue: $383 billion</li>
                <li>Gross margin: 43%</li>
                <li>Net margin: 25%</li>
                <li>Free cash flow: $100+ billion</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Conclusion</strong>: High gross margin + stable cash flow + brand moat (ecosystem), a typical value investment target.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h3>üîç Google (GOOG)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>2023 Financial data (simplified):
            <ul>
                <li>Revenue: $307 billion</li>
                <li>Gross margin: 56%</li>
                <li>Net margin: 22%</li>
                <li>Main business: Advertising revenue (accounting for > 80%)</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Conclusion</strong>: Advertising business growth is slowing, but cloud computing and AI are becoming new growth points.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <p>üëâ Comparison:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Both are cash flow machines, but Apple is more stable, Google is more dependent on advertising.</li>
        <li>Investment perspective: Apple is "defensive", Google is "growth + technology innovation".</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>1.4 Common Investor Mistakes</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Only looking at stock price curves</strong>: Ignoring profit quality, easily deceived by short-term fluctuations.</li>
        <li><strong>Chasing news and hot spots</strong>: Forgetting to research company fundamentals.</li>
        <li><strong>Underestimating the importance of financial statements</strong>: In fact, gross margin and cash flow are the keys to whether a company can survive.</li>
    </ul>
    
